Susan Murray traces these wide-ranging debates within and beyond the television industry, positioning the story of color television, which was replete with false starts, failure, and ingenuity, as central to the broader history of twentieth-century visual culture. In so doing, she shows how color television disrupted and reframed the very idea of television while it simultaneously revealed the tensions about technology's relationship to consumerism, human sight, and the natural world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aColor televisionxHistory. 0aTelevision broadcastingxHistoryzUnited States. 0aTelevision broadcastingxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aTelevision broadcastingxTechnological innovationszUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aKatherine Singer Kovacs Award winner.  aSCMS award winners.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106963320 cprintz978082237121240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822371700423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822371700/original  a978-3-11-069633-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles